The following pseudocode is a sample demonstration of how to navigate a StaleConnectionException: 

// Initiate a userTransaction
javax.transaction.UserTransaction transaction = getSessionContext().getUserTransaction();

// 'retryIfFail' establishes whether to attempt a do over or not
// 'attemptCount' records the number of attempts that have been tried
boolean retryIfFail = false;
int attemptCount = 0;

java.sql.Connection connection = null;
java.sql.Statement statement = null;

do {
    try {
        // start a transaction
        transaction.begin();

        // Assumes that a datasource is already fetched from JNDI
        connection = ds.getConnection();
        connection.setAutoCommit(false);
        statement = connection.createStatement();
        statement.execute("INSERT INTO EMPLOYEE_DETAILS VALUES(0011, 'John', 'DOE')");

        // commit the transaction
        transaction.commit();
        retryIfFail = false;
    } 
    catch(java.sql.SQLException sqlException){
        // If the error denotes the connection is dated, then rollback and try the same process
        if (com.ibm.websphere.rsadapter.WSCallHelper.getDataStoreHelper(ds)
             .isConnectionError(sqlException)){
            try {
                transaction.rollback();
            } 
            catch (java.lang.Exception ex) {
                // handle exception
                // generally, this can be overlooked
            }

            if (attemptCount < 2) {
                retryIfFail = true;
                attemptCount++;
            } 
            else {
                retryIfFail = false;
            }
        }
        else{
            // handle other database-related exceptions
            retryIfFail = false;
        }
    } 
    finally {
        // always cleanup JDBC resources
        try {
            if(statement != null) statement.close();
        } 
        catch (java.sql.SQLException sqlE) {
            // usually can be disregarded
        }

        try {
            if(connection != null) connection.close();
        } 
        catch (java.sql.SQLException sqlE) {
            // usually can be disregarded
        }
    }
} while (retryIfFail);

Details about WebSphere Connection Pooling are in the WebSphere Application Server Knowledge Center's Connection pooling article [https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/SSAW57_8.5.5/com.ibm.websphere.nd.doc/ae/cdat_conpool.html]

The Knowledge Center also contains details about the StaleConnectionException error in the Exceptions pertaining to data access article [https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/SSAW57_8.5.5/com.ibm.websphere.nd.doc/ae/cdat_daexcp.html]

